headline: Delta Air Lines sees higher fares, demand recovery ahead
summary: STORY: Shares of Delta Air Lines rose as much as nine percent Thursday morning after the company issued an upbeat forecast and posted quarterly earnings that topped expectations.The Atlanta-based airline said its sales have accelerated over the past six weeks everywhere it flies, and also reported a rebound in business travel bookings.A sharp reduction in airline seat capacity in the U.S. market has driven up ticket prices. This contributed to Delta's higher unit revenue, a key indicator for pricing power, in the September quarter, following a decline in the previous quarter.One analyst told Reuters he expects Delta's revenue growth to extend into 2026 and sees it and peer United Airlines benefiting from their premium offerings.CEO Ed Bastian said Delta is also "well-positioned" to deliver revenue growth as well as margin expansion next year.Its outlook, however, does not factor in any fallout from the U.S. government shutdown. More than 13,000 flights have been delayed this week amid staffing shortages at air-traffic control facilities. With the federal employees working without pay, the staffing situation could worsen.Despite lingering economic uncertainty, analysts say the company's diversified revenue streams have made it better equipped than some of its rivals to shield its earnings.
